# GIT WORKFLOW

## Branch Strategy

```
ideate/{{TAG}}              ← main idea branch (best version lives here)
├── ideate/{{TAG}}-v1       ← first refinement
├── ideate/{{TAG}}-v2       ← second refinement
├── ideate/{{TAG}}-dir-A    ← direction A exploration
├── ideate/{{TAG}}-dir-B    ← direction B exploration
└── ideate/{{TAG}}-dir-C    ← direction C exploration
```

## Version Control Operations

```bash
# Before exploring a new direction
git checkout ideate/{{TAG}}
git checkout -b ideate/{{TAG}}-dir-<name>

# After direction is evaluated
git add doc/agent/ && git commit -m "dir-<name>: <verdict>"
git notes add -m "Direction <name>: <summary>" HEAD

# If direction is promising → merge back
git checkout ideate/{{TAG}} && git merge ideate/{{TAG}}-dir-<name>

# If direction is dead end → leave branch, go back
git checkout ideate/{{TAG}}

# New idea version (after selecting best direction)
git checkout ideate/{{TAG}}
git checkout -b ideate/{{TAG}}-v<N>
# ... refine ...
git add -A && git commit -m "v<N>: <what changed>"
git checkout ideate/{{TAG}} && git merge ideate/{{TAG}}-v<N>

# Checkpoint before risky decision
git add -A && git commit -m "checkpoint: before <decision>"
```

Each idea version gets:
- A card file: `doc/agent/idea_versions/v<N>_<slug>.md`
- A git branch: `ideate/{{TAG}}-v<N>`
- A git note on the merge commit summarizing the version

## Merging Two Directions

If user wants to combine aspects of multiple directions:
```bash
git checkout ideate/{{TAG}}
git checkout -b ideate/{{TAG}}-dir-<merged_name>
# Write merged idea, validate the combination, commit
```

